  "answer": "The following works in the corpus open by addressing or invoking the audience:\n\n1. **Andreas** (cynewulf-andreas-07b573, ch. 1, p-868413): Opens with \"We have heard of heroes in ages past, / of twelve true thanes under the turning stars\" — the Old English bardic 'wē gehȳrdon' (we have heard) formula invites the listener into a shared recollection, a conventional Anglo-Saxon audience invocation.\n\n2. **Juliana** (cynewulf-juliana-9a2157, ch. 1, p-529b94): Opens with \"Hark! We have heard it, a history for heroes\" — 'Hark!' is a direct call to the audience's attention; this is the clearest audience-invocation opening in the Old English works.\n\n3. **Kalpabuddha** (unknown-kalpabuddha-d760dc, ch. 1, p-e1c8df): Opens with \"This is the royal command of the Lord, the divine Buddha, this great instruction must be heeded, listen to all the mantras\" — 'must be heeded' and 'listen' are direct imperatives addressed to the reader/audience.\n\n4. **San Hyan Kamahayanikan** (unknown-san-hyan-kamahayanikan-2a0c19, ch. 1, p-6eb5c0): Opens with \"Come, child, I shall teach you the Great Vehicle, the method of the Path of the Master of Mantras. You are a worthy vessel for the Great Path.\" — explicit second-person address to the student/reader.\n\n5. **San Hyan Tattvajnana** (unknown-san-hyan-tattvajnana-1f29bd, ch. 1, p-d53c24): Opens with \"Now, this must be heeded by the practitioner of the sacred duty who wishes to be released from the cycle of rebirth... That is what you must first understand\" — the second-person 'you must' is a direct instruction to the audience.\n\nWithin the **Old English Elegies** collection (unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e), which is catalogued as one work with 17 chapters (each a distinct poem), the first chapter does not address the audience, but four individual poems open with audience address:\n- Ch. 6, Maxims I (p-84cf09): \"Question me with wise words! Do not let your spirit be hidden\" — explicit second-person address.\n- Ch. 8, The Husband's Message (p-58bec2): \"Now I specially shall speak to you\" — direct 'you'.\n- Ch. 12, Vainglory (p-946b37): \"Listen, a wise sage told me in days of yore\" — 'Listen' invokes the audience.\n- Ch. 15 (p-583181): \"Will you, eager hero, greet a curious man\" — explicit second-person question to the audience.\n\nBorderline: **Zurückforderung der Denkfreiheit** (Fichte, johann-gottlieb-fichte-zuruckforderung-der-denkfreiheit-bookde) has a Preface (ch. 1) that does not address the audience directly, but its main Speech (ch. 2, p-6e07a5) opens with \"The times of barbarism are over, you peoples\" — sustained direct address. If the Speech itself counts as the work's opening, Fichte belongs on this list.",
